{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528120","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528120"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:37:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:37:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14265"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14265","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14265"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.08,0.11,0.74,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6960"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94365"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6960","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6960"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14265"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77423"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1165"},{"type":"tags","id":"2040"},{"type":"tags","id":"3997"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16303"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31259"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31260"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/94365"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 84-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a two-day history of increasing lower back pain. This is associated with a tingling sensation running down his left thigh. Three days ago, he fell over and hurt his back while gardening. His medical history includes hypertension and atrial fibrillation, for which he takes perindopril and warfarin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears uncomfortable. His pulse rate is 90/min, blood pressure 116/72 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. He is unable to stand straight and is more comfortable with hip flexion. There is some numbness over the anterior aspect of his left thigh. The rest of the examination is unremarkable. A CT scan is performed (Image 1, 2).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal an INR of 4.2 (2.0-3.0) and haemoglobin of 116 g/L (128-175).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Leaking abdominal aortic aneurysm","Psoas abscess","Prolapsed intervertebral disc","Psoas haematoma","Left renal abscess"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT images show a large left \u003Cstrong\u003Epsoas haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E, which is the correct diagnosis. This condition is a known complication of anticoagulation therapy, particularly in elderly patients. The patient\u0027s history of warfarin use for atrial fibrillation, recent fall, and supratherapeutic INR of 4.2 all contribute to the increased risk of bleeding. The symptoms of lower back pain, hip flexion for comfort, and femoral nerve compression (causing numbness in the anterior thigh) are classic presentations of a psoas haematoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eleaking abdominal aortic aneurysm\u003C/strong\u003E (AAA) can present with back pain and can be life-threatening. However, the CT images do not show an AAA, and the patient\u0027s vital signs are stable, making this diagnosis less likely. Additionally, a leaking AAA would typically cause more severe pain and potentially signs of shock.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epsoas abscess\u003C/strong\u003E can present with similar symptoms to a psoas haematoma, including back pain and hip flexion. However, patients with psoas abscess typically have fever, elevated white cell count, and a history of infection. The acute onset following a fall and the patient being on anticoagulation therapy with a high INR makes a haematoma much more likely than an abscess.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eprolapsed intervertebral disc\u003C/strong\u003E could cause back pain and neurological symptoms. However, the CT images clearly show a psoas haematoma, which better explains the patient\u0027s symptoms. Additionally, disc prolapse typically causes sciatica (pain radiating down the back of the leg) rather than anterior thigh symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft renal abscess\u003C/strong\u003E would typically present with flank pain, fever, and urinary symptoms. The CT images do not show any renal pathology, and the clinical presentation is not consistent with a renal abscess. The patient\u0027s symptoms are better explained by the psoas haematoma visible on imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of a psoas haematoma depends on its size and the patient\u0027s clinical status. In this case, the priority would be to reverse the anticoagulation, potentially with vitamin K or prothrombin complex concentrate, depending on the urgency. The patient should be monitored closely for expansion of the haematoma or development of compartment syndrome. In severe cases, surgical evacuation may be necessary, but many cases can be managed conservatively with careful monitoring and supportive care.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Psoas haematoma is a potential complication of anticoagulation therapy, especially in elderly patients.","CT imaging is the gold standard for diagnosing psoas haematoma.","Symptoms of psoas haematoma can include lower back pain, hip flexion, and femoral nerve compression."],"references":["Guild TT, Crawford AM, Striano BM, et al. The epidemiology and management of iliopsoas hematoma with femoral nerve palsy: A descriptive systematic review of 174 cases. Injury 2023; 54:280-87."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77423"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14265"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21080"},{"type":"media","id":"21081"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21080","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21080"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4OHc831NU3BL3DqcmJ0R1ClibEs3aG.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4OHc831NU3BL3DqcmJ0R1ClibEs3aG.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":821,"height":695}},{"type":"media","id":"21081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21081"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ta9kjb5868uEaAOczx60Azv7n5wHL8.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ta9kjb5868uEaAOczx60Azv7n5wHL8.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":864,"height":822}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77423"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-23T19:46:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-23T19:48:10+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6960"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94365"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":nu